thread.title: Aust. stocks open weaker after volatile session on Wall Street
thread.title_full: Aust. stocks open weaker after volatile session on Wall Street

author: John Conroy
title: Aust. stocks open weaker after volatile session on Wall Street
text:
The Australian sharemarket ticked down slightly at the open following choppy trade on Wall Street overnight ahead of next week's key interest rate decision in the US.
At the 10.15am (AEST) official market open, the benchmark S & P/ASX200 index had declined 5.4 points, or 0.11 per cent, to 5089.6, while the broader All Ordinaries dropped 4 points, or 0.08 per cent, to 5113.
The open followed half-a-percentage point gains on Wall Street, after the markets reversed losses earlier in the day, and came despite 3 to 4 per cent improvements in oil prices overnight.
IG market analyst Angus Nicholson said a slow start was envisioned today but that markets remained highly volatile as the US Federal Reserve's monetary policy decision on September 17 neared.
In local economic news today, the Australian Bureau of Statistics releases lending finance figures.
The Australian market had its second-worst day since May 2012 yesterday as banks led broadbased selling on poor Wall Street leads.
At the 4.15pm (AEST) official market close, the benchmark S & P/ASX200 index had fallen 126.1 points, or 2.42 per cent, to 5095, while the broader All Ordinaries had lost 120 points, or 2.29 per cent, to 5116.9.
Originally published as Aust. stocks open weaker
